<paragraph id="8BBBF17A8411FFF958ACFEB84C4AFD86" blockId="1.[151,1436,325,523]" pageId="1" pageNumber="56">
Nine species are listed in this genus (
<bibRefCitation id="EF958C8B8411FFF95A0DFEB84A23FED1" author="Mound" box="[566,809,325,349]" pageId="1" pageNumber="56" refString="Mound, L. A. &amp; Tree, D. (2009) Identification and host-plant associations of Australian Sericothripinae (Thysanoptera, Thripidae). Zootaxa, 1983, 1 - 22." type="journal article" year="2009">
Mound &amp; Tree, 
<number id="3DCCE35D8411FFF95AD5FEB84A23FED1" box="[750,809,325,349]" pageId="1" pageNumber="56" value="2009.0">2009</number>
</bibRefCitation>
; 
<bibRefCitation id="EF958C8B8411FFF95B0EFEB84AC5FED1" author="Mound" box="[821,975,325,349]" pageId="1" pageNumber="56" refString="Mound, L. A. 2011. Thysanoptera (thrips) of the world - a checklist. Available online at: http: // anic. ento. csiro. au / thrips / htm. (accessed 2 April 2011)." type="journal article" year="2011">
Mound, 
<number id="3DCCE35D8411FFF95BAFFEB84AC5FED1" box="[916,975,325,349]" pageId="1" pageNumber="56" value="2011.0">2011</number>
</bibRefCitation>
). Most of these are based on micropterae (
<figureCitation id="133FEDFF8411FFF958A4FE9A482CFEF3" box="[159,294,359,383]" captionStart="FIGURES 18 – 20. S" captionStartId="5.[151,264,924,947]" captionTargetBox="[154,1436,193,903]" captionTargetId="figure@5.[151,1436,193,903]" captionTargetPageId="5" captionText="FIGURES 18 – 20. S. houji: (18) macropterous female, (19) micropterous female, (20) micropterous male (Scale bar = 200 microns)." httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/278574/files/figure.png" pageId="1" pageNumber="56">
Figs 
<number id="3DCCE35D8411FFF958E6FE9A482CFEF3" box="[221,294,359,383]" pageId="1" pageNumber="56" value="19.5" valueMax="20.0" valueMin="19.0">19–20</number>
</figureCitation>
), but some from both micropterous and macropterous morphs (
<figureCitation id="133FEDFF8411FFF95C21FE9A4D78FEF3" box="[1050,1138,359,383]" captionStart="FIGURES 18 – 20. S" captionStartId="5.[151,264,924,947]" captionTargetBox="[154,1436,193,903]" captionTargetId="figure@5.[151,1436,193,903]" captionTargetPageId="5" captionText="FIGURES 18 – 20. S. houji: (18) macropterous female, (19) micropterous female, (20) micropterous male (Scale bar = 200 microns)." httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/278574/files/figure.png" pageId="1" pageNumber="56">
Fig. 
<number id="3DCCE35D8411FFF95C68FE9A4D78FEF3" box="[1107,1138,359,383]" pageId="1" pageNumber="56" value="18.0">18</number>
</figureCitation>
). These species have the abdominal terga completely covered with microtrichia medially (Fig. 
<number id="3DCCE35D8411FFF95B9AFE774ABAFE2E" box="[929,944,394,418]" pageId="1" pageNumber="56" value="6.0">6</number>
) (
<bibRefCitation id="EF958C8B8411FFF95BFCFE774DB3FE2E" author="Mound" box="[967,1209,394,418]" pageId="1" pageNumber="56" refString="Mound, L. A. &amp; Tree, D. (2009) Identification and host-plant associations of Australian Sericothripinae (Thysanoptera, Thripidae). Zootaxa, 1983, 1 - 22." type="journal article" year="2009">
Mound &amp; Tree, 
<number id="3DCCE35D8411FFF95C46FE774DB3FE2E" box="[1149,1209,394,418]" pageId="1" pageNumber="56" value="2009.0">2009</number>
</bibRefCitation>
), whereas species in the other two genera have closely spaced rows of microtrichia only laterally on the abdominal terga (Figs 
<number id="3DCCE35D8411FFF95D59FE504C9AFE49" box="[1378,1424,429,453]" pageId="1" pageNumber="56" value="4.5" valueMax="5.0" valueMin="4.0">4–5</number>
). Species of 
<taxonomicName id="4C048AF98411FFF9592AFE2D48AFFE64" box="[273,421,464,488]" class="Insecta" family="Thripidae" genus="Hydatothrips" higherTaxonomySource="GBIF" kingdom="Animalia" order="Thysanoptera" pageId="1" pageNumber="56" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="genus">
<emphasis id="B9702D688411FFF9592AFE2D48AFFE64" box="[273,421,464,488]" italics="true" pageId="1" pageNumber="56">Hydatothrips</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
have the metasternum with a median V-shaped apodeme (Figs 
<number id="3DCCE35D8411FFF95C5EFE324D9BFE6B" box="[1125,1169,463,487]" pageId="1" pageNumber="56" value="1.5" valueMax="2.0" valueMin="1.0">1–2</number>
), whereas this apodeme is T-shaped or Y-shaped in 
<taxonomicName id="4C048AF98411FFF959FCFE0E4B88FD87" box="[455,642,499,523]" class="Insecta" family="Thripidae" genus="Neohydatothrips" kingdom="Animalia" order="Thysanoptera" pageId="1" pageNumber="56" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="genus">
<emphasis id="B9702D688411FFF959FCFE0E4B88FD87" box="[455,642,499,523]" italics="true" pageId="1" pageNumber="56">Neohydatothrips</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
(Fig. 
<number id="3DCCE35D8411FFF95AFDFE0F4BDEFD86" box="[710,724,498,522]" pageId="1" pageNumber="56" value="3.0">3</number>
) and 
<taxonomicName id="4C048AF98411FFF95B28FE0E4A96FD87" box="[787,924,499,523]" class="Insecta" family="Thripidae" genus="Sericothrips" kingdom="Animalia" order="Thysanoptera" pageId="1" pageNumber="56" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="genus">
<emphasis id="B9702D688411FFF95B28FE0E4A96FD87" box="[787,924,499,523]" italics="true" pageId="1" pageNumber="56">Sericothrips</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
(
<bibRefCitation id="EF958C8B8411FFF95B90FE0F4D3CFD86" author="Wang" box="[939,1078,498,522]" pageId="1" pageNumber="56" refString="Wang, C. L. (2007) Hydatothrips and Neohydatothrips (Thysanoptera, Thripidae) of East and South Asia with three new species from Taiwan. Zootaxa, 1575, 47 - 68." type="journal article" year="2007">
Wang, 
<number id="3DCCE35D8411FFF95BC0FE0F4D3CFD86" box="[1019,1078,498,522]" pageId="1" pageNumber="56" value="2007.0">2007</number>
</bibRefCitation>
; 
<bibRefCitation id="EF958C8B8411FFF95C79FE0F4C3EFD86" author="Mound" box="[1090,1332,498,522]" pageId="1" pageNumber="56" refString="Mound, L. A. &amp; Tree, D. (2009) Identification and host-plant associations of Australian Sericothripinae (Thysanoptera, Thripidae). Zootaxa, 1983, 1 - 22." type="journal article" year="2009">
Mound &amp; Tree, 
<number id="3DCCE35D8411FFF95CCCFE0F4C3EFD86" box="[1271,1332,498,522]" pageId="1" pageNumber="56" value="2009.0">2009</number>
